MSG-----------
Date: Sun, 25 Apr 1993 16:02:36 +0100
From: Paul Hickman <ph@doc.ic.ac.uk>
To: AMOS@xamiga.linet.org
Subject: There are more questions than answers

Hi, I've been away from the net for the past three weeks, so there's
loads a E-Mail here awaiting reply - some of these may now be a little
old. There's also a few questions (And plea's) of my own.

Jean-Francois Dreyfuss asked about LINE INPUT in amos pro. I've also
had this problem with the orignal amos, ever since v1.1, and I don't
know the solution. I eventually decided the best way was to write the
length of the string first (Usually as a word), the write the string.
Then to read it, I use the INPUT$ command. This of course only works
when AMOS writes the file.

On the subject of I/O, a tip for reading / writing numbers. To store
the value of A, instead of PRINT#1,A try

PRINT #1,chr$(int(a/256));chr$(a and 255);
			(assuming A is between 0 and 65536)

Or alternatively

PRINT #1,chr$(peek(varptr(a));chr$(peek(varptr(a)+1));chr$(peek(varptr(a)+2));
chr$(peek(varptr(a)+3));
			(To write any possible A)

Although this is more code (And slightly hacky, especially the second way)
all numbers are stored in exactly four bytes, and not one per character. To
read one of these numbers, use

A=asc(input$(1,1))*$1000000+asc(input$(1,1))*$10000+asc(input$(1,1))*$100+
asc(input$(1,1))

Of course the PRINT# / INPUT# commands on AMOS are very slow anyway, and
if your trying to shift a large amount of data, you may as well put it in
a bank.



Mark hammar asks about switching between two screens. The answer is to
use the command SCREEN TO FRONT <n>, to make one screen appear in front
of the other. On a similar vein, the other day while mucking around,
I wrote a routine to do screen copies by seemingly random mossaic tiles
of varaible size. I'll try to get this onto the net in the next few days.



David Tiberio asks if AMOS works on an A500 with about 800K free. Well AMOS
works on a half meg machine, so I'd imagine so (Don't know about pro though).


Michael Cox's bug report form - great idea, but didn't you forget the small
matter of Country? On the subject of bugs, you know how some software 
companies describe them as "undocumented features", well I've found an
undocumented feature of AMOS (At least I can't find it in any document
I've got), which is an exculsive or command Xor. However, I'd advise against
using it, as it fails to compile (Or at least it did on compiler V1.34 - I've
never tried it on later versions).


By the way, can someone send me the upgrade document of version V1.35 (AMOS
and Compiler) - What changes were made? I got this version off a magazine
cover disk.

Finally, when trying to compile a rather long program the other day, I ran
out of memory, so I thought to myself "Does this Compiler.AMOS need to be
50K ?". The answer I found, is that it only needs to be 1700 bytes, although
you can't crunch programs then. (I know you can use acmp from direct mode,
but I can't be bothered to enter the command line). I'll copy this up,
with the mossaic screen copy, and text routines soon.

Did I say finally? Oops, I've read the programmers newsgroup now, and I'd like
to add a few comments to these amos criticisms. Firstly, there are two main
areas, in which I think amos is lacking :-

  - Support of floating point numbers. Could we at least have double precision.
    I sometimes get errors with numbers with only 4 significant figures.

  - Variable types. AMOS has all the graphical manipulation commands you need,
    to produce a professional looking game, but lacks the record structures,
    emmunerated types, and dynamic pointer structures needed to provide the
    gameplay. I mean Integers, Reals, and Strings? I know AMOS is a basic,
    but it has evolved in every other area. We could at least have a record
    structure, which could be used as array elements.

    As an example, I'm currently trying to write an RPG, and the only way I
    can easily store the statistics of each monster, spell, item, etc. is
    to poke & peek direct from a memory bank, which is appauling (almost as
    appauling as my spelling)

  - There was some mention of an NCOMMAND extension to allow use of intuition
    does anyone have further details? Michael cox said this was a bit pointless
    as you need to push Amiga-A to see it, but If I remember there are AMOS TO
    BACK and AMOS TO FRONT commands, and you can compile programs to run in 
    the background.

    By the way, does anyone know what happens if two compiled programs are
    running simultanously, and you press Amiga-A from the workbench. Which
    program do you go to?

That's it for now. remember to put a MULTI WAIT VBL command in any loop
where speed isn't essential - It make amos more system friendly.


 

